These lessons they learned so well that when government officials in Shanghai, who suddenly started to change the course this summer through the low birth rate and the ageing population, and encouraged young couples to have more than one child, their answer was immediate and final: "Neither so."
We have already invested all our time and energy in a child.
For a second child there is nothing left, said Wang, 31, a staff manager with an 8-month old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one-child policy in China, which has produced two generations of notablely thick, abandoned children, who are lovingly called "little emperors", a population crisis is emerging in the country.
The average birth rate has fallen to 1.8 children per couple compared to 6 at the time this policy came into force, the UN
Population Issues Division, while the number of population aged 60 and over in 2020 is expected to rise from 16.7% of the population by 2050 to 31.1% of the population. This is well above the global average of about 20 percent.
The imbalance is stronger in rich coastal cities with educated populations, such as Shanghai.
Last year, 60-year-olds and olders accounted for almost 22 percent of Shanghai‚Äôs reported residents, while birth rates were below one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, head of the Shanghai Urban Population and Family Planning Commission, said that couples in the productive age need to have babies in order to "help reduce the ratio of the ageing population and reduce the labour shortage of the future".
Shanghai will soon be "as old -- but not as rich -- as the industrialized countries, like Japan and Sweden," she said.
A gradual relaxation
Ensuring in the country's Constitution in 1978, China's one-child struggle is probably the most controversial order introduced by the ruling Communist Party to date.
Couples who violate this policy have to expect enormous fines -- up to their three-fold annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination at their workplace.
Chinese representatives have attributed it to this policy that the critical demand of natural land resources could be avoided, whereas human rights representatives have condemned abuses in the enforcement of politics.
In rural regions some officials have forced pregnant women who have already had a child to quit.
Many couples also had sexual selective abortions, resulting in an unnaturally high relationship between men and women.
Over the last few years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their attitude towards one-child policy.
In 2004 they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities and cases where both husband and wife were single children -- and in 2007 the tone of many hard slogans was reduced.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the University of Beijing's Institute of Population Research, said that government representatives recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children in whom a partner is an individual child.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city in July to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births.
Posters who taught families to have only one child were replaced almost overnight by guidelines describing in detail who would be in charge of a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city administration has sent out urban employees and volunteers for family planning to visit couples at home and to post information sheets under the doors.
She also asked to provide psychological and financial advice for those who have more than one child.
The reaction was not very encouraging, said family planning representatives.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a rural small town in Shanghai's outer areas said that a recovery in the applications of couples who want a second child after the start of the campaign, the urban districts do not report any change.
For example, only four to five applications are still received per month for the Huinan municipality with a population of 115,000.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that despite the campaign, the expected number of births in the city for 2010 will still be around 165,000 -- slightly higher than 2009, but lower than 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee of the Shanghai community of Caolu, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don't want to have children anymore.
They want to give her the best, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said that they would like to have two children and that this would be permitted by law.
But they have, like many Chinese people, only a minor health and life insurance of the government.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West falsify the one-child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is pregnant with her first child in the seventh month.
Yes, we are deprived of the opportunity to have more than one child.
The problem is not simply a policy.
The problem is money.
Other couples give psychological reasons for their reluctance.
Wang, the head of staff, said she only wanted one child because she was also an individual child. "We were the focus of the family and used to everyone taking care of us.
We are not used to taking care of others, nor do we really want to."
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old who owns a translation company, said it more unmistakably.
For parents from the middle class with double careers, through which the birth rate drops, he said, it is about to be successful and for that one must be selfish.
The age group of today's 20- to 39-year-olds grew up to see their parents fighting during the early days of the Chinese capitalism experiment and they don't want such a life for themselves, he said.
A single child, he said, also places enormous demands on the time of parents.
A mother must give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there's the space question -- "You have to remodel your apartment" -- and the life plan -- "When the child is 9 months old, you have to already have a curriculum for the best preschools."
Most of his friends are ready to go through this once, Chen said, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to achieve a higher standard of living, he said.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
UNO Group drafts emission reduction plan
The UN-funded climate conference, which has so far been characterised by wild poses and mutual accusations, again focused on Friday with the publication of a document that sets out for the next 40 years an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases, with industrial nations having to learn the biggest burdens in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement on greenhouse gas regulation, has shown both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But he was considered to be an important progress in a negotiation that is about to take place, since next week more than 100 top politicians from all over the world will arrive in Copenhagen.
The text, formulated by a specially created UN working group, is silent about the amount of money that rich countries should give to the poor countries so that they can cope with global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of key options, including how industrial and large emerging countries can limit their carbon emissions and how high the global temperature increase should be, which policy-makers would contribute.
The process is given great flexibility, says John Coequyt, executive representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who designed the six-page document, has summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the leading UN climate protection representative, Yvo de Boer, called "the big whole".
It shows the outline of a possible agreement in which industrial nations would jointly reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 limit values, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent in the same period.
Together, countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community has also given the Friday talks a boost by its assurance that over the next three years it will provide 3.6 billion US dollars per year to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change - from mastering floods and droughts to avoiding deforestation.
Friday nevertheless brought the same verbal fireworks that had determined the discussions last week.
The American climate specialist Todd Stern has rejected formulations requiring binding reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialised countries, compared with voluntary reductions for larger emerging countries, if these are not financed by the industrial nations.
This move announced that the Obama government is driving a harder line with China than the Bush government did not even two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without larger emerging economies standing up and taking action, said Star, who also complained that the text would not go far enough to ensure that the reductions could also be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern gave his opinion an hour after the Chinese Vice-President He Yafei declared that the leading American climate negotiator was either lacking in "reason" or it was "very irresponsible" of him that he said at the beginning of the week that the United States would not help China effectively to master global warming.
The future economic march towards the world's major powers has opened up between industrial nations as well as between industrial nations and emerging economies.
The current struggle relates equally to the rescue of individual economies, as well as to the rescue of the planet, with China and the United States concerned due to their corresponding commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take more courageous measures.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the large powers are fighting for those who should bear the cost of brakes on greenhouse gas emissions, since even affected countries have taken a more aggressive approach to making the countries with very high greenhouse gas emissions account for their actions.
This is clearly a game from which a new economic domination will develop, says Ulate, who is also a regional climate change consultant for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the effects of climate change stated that they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although the leading participants say that the talks will lead to a political agreement at best.
The alliance of the small island states with 43 members presented a draft contract of 24 pages in the early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the offensive of the small island states "is exerting political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now united and demand action from emerging countries, such as China and India.
The talks were given a new urgency when delegates focused on the fact that most of the open questions still need to be resolved before the leaders arrived to reach an agreement.
High-ranking representatives, such as the Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister, fled their planes and raced through the steps of the Bella Center to meet behind closed doors and press conferences to complete claims negotiated during the next week.
The pure extent of the assembly -- 13,000 people go to and out in the Congress Centre every day, guitar-playing activists organise nocturnal shows in which they make fun of the countries they think are betraying and selling, and contract drafts are passed on by hand rather than by e-mail -- is already a challenge.
The intensity is just beginning to build up: almost all the important ministers are here now and from Wednesday 60 leaders will be in Copenhagen.
We come to the Upper League, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice-President of the Global Policy of the Organization Conservation International.
The heavy weights are coming.
