The cradle of the dinosaurs
Tawa hallee looked like many other meat-eating dinosaurs: The two-metre-long and 1,50-metre-long animal ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would be nothing special.
But Tawa hallee was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in Science magazine of Thursday.
The animal lived some 215 million years ago in today‚Äôs New Mexico, which was then on the equator in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pang√§a.
Tawa opens a new window to the early evolution of the dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us a lot about the relationship, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began to dig on the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We have sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the trias, reports team member Randall Irmis from the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as a new species.
In the course of the excavation, they gathered the remains of a total of five individuals.
Fund confirms theories on early Dino history
The name Tawa comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an extraordinary find: "Dinosaur fossils from the trias are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments can be found."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share enthusiasm.
This find is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of the dinosaurs, says about Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current opinion, the dinosaurs appeared for the first time about 230 million years ago.
Many of the oldest fossils, however, are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these Ur-Dinos is usually controversial.
For example, the experts debate when the lizards split into their three main development lines: the meat-eating theropods, which later included the tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the four-legged Sauropods and their relatives, and the plants eat Ornithischia (Birds‚Äô Sauriers), which included, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
After analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
He has an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
At the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of air bags, as they also possess the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags the breathing of the birds is more efficient than those of the mammals.
At Tawa hallee, the bones of the spine were apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the relative line of the huge Sauropods later also had air bags and lightweight bones, probably the common ancestor of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migration waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known so far lived in South America, the researchers concluded that the lizards appeared there for the first time.
As a result, the three lines of development separated early and spread from South America across all continents, which at that time still formed a single land mass as a supercontinent Pang√§a.
The fact that the team together with Tawa hallae found the remains of two other not particularly closely related theropods speaks for this.
The three cannot originate from a common, immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe that there were at least three migration waves to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of the dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says the Bonn palaeontologist Martin Sander.
In his opinion, a distorted picture could arise, because in South America, there are just a lot of primitive Dino fossils that have been preserved, while on other continents, there is hardly anything to be found.
As the dinosaurs managed to develop from a relatively rare sideline of the reptile tribe to the dominant agricultural vertebrates of the middle age, is still enigmatic.
During the trias, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and the fly-sauriers and with numerous other lizards.
Toward the end of the trias, the dinosaurs spread all over the world and developed many new species, while the kinship died on the border from the trias to the law.
Success story did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass death that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so that they could beat the competition out of the field.
The success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact of a group of animals gave rise to bloom, which had also developed in the trias and since then had a shadow existence: the mammals.
