Some see images in a state of alertness and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
Not only in the mentally ill and in the intoxication of drugs, the boundaries between imagination and reality are blurred.
As long as it happens in sleep, everything is fine.
If we lie in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we may freely surrender to the wildest ideas and imaginations.
However, those who experience traumatic conditions in the wake, see and hear things that others do not see or hear, in the modern Western world are usually considered crazy or drug addicts, at least as special.
However, such images and voices do not arise only in the psychologically ill or in the intoxication of drugs.
Blame is our imagination: the same neuronal processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels sometimes make sure that the boundaries between dream, madness and reality fade.
Dream-like altered awareness states can occur in a wide variety of forms, at best we call them visions, in the worst case madness.
Even though triggering and effect may differ, the visions of mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, Shamanian rapture states, psychoses and hallucinations can be traced back to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of the neural messengers of the brain - most importantly dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin and acetylcholine - is removed and the interaction of different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and insane thoughts occur very often during a schizophrenic psychosis.
