The connection of madness and dream has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle understood hallucinations as a form of dream in alert condition, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, observed in 1861 a "great similarity of error with dream conditions", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis, with all inconsistencies, delusions, sensory illusions of such".
