The tricks are cruel reality
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in life, and in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, those affected can no longer distinguish between the interior and the outside world, they get into an excruciating state that can lead to hallucinations, size, relationship or persecution.
Especially common is listening to voices - voices that command, comment or dialogue.
Also optical hallucinations are not uncommon.
The affected person can no longer separate important things from the unimportant, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like the dream, the psychosis also opens the locks for a flood of ideas and fantasies that originate from deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in the psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, Chief Physician of the Department of General Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital.
