Support for brake maneuvers in critical situations is now compulsory
As with the ABS anti-lock braking system at the time, and just as with the ESP stability control system, the emergency braking aid systems must become a requirement in European cars.
In fact, they are already compulsory for all newly approved passenger cars and light mini-carriers, and for the remaining vehicles a time limit has been set until the end of February 2011.
The action taken by the European Union aims to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many accidents due to their operation.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical brake maneuver, which the system detects on the brake pedal using the brake strength executed by the driver.
However, this system does not exercise this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident did not have to enter the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not braked with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, intervenes in the braking system with maximum force and thus reduces the braking time and thus also the brake distance that a car takes during the braking process.
According to an EU study, every year up to 1,100 fatal accidents affecting pedestrians could be prevented if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assistant.
There would be even fewer accidents - one expects that every fourth accident could be prevented with personal damage - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (by radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system helps him increase the pressure on the brake pedal if it becomes necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is inevitable, the brake assistant exerts the maximum pressure on the brakes in order to keep the damage as low as possible.
